<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="166" pageId="7" pageNumber="165" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1795,2036]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1437,151,578]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="166" pageId="7" pageNumber="165">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1795,1820]" pageId="7" pageNumber="165">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Metope wide, with distinct median carina running from its upper margin to metopoclypeal suture and very weak sublateral carinae visible only in its upper part and joined median carina below upper margin of metope (
<bibRefCitation box="[158,512,1867,1892]" pageId="7" pageNumber="165" refId="ref6203" refString="Gnezdilov, V. M. &amp; Poggi, F. (2014) First record of Nearctic issid planthopper Thionia simplex (Hemiptera: Fulgoroidea: Issidae) from Europe. Zoosystematica Rossica, 23 (2), 238 - 241." type="journal article">Gnezdilov &amp; Poggi 2014, fig. 3</bibRefCitation>
); lateral margins convex. Coryphe transverse, 1.5 times as wide as long at midline, with weak incomplete median carina (
<bibRefCitation box="[581,940,1903,1928]" pageId="7" pageNumber="165" refId="ref6203" refString="Gnezdilov, V. M. &amp; Poggi, F. (2014) First record of Nearctic issid planthopper Thionia simplex (Hemiptera: Fulgoroidea: Issidae) from Europe. Zoosystematica Rossica, 23 (2), 238 - 241." type="journal article">Gnezdilov &amp; Poggi 2014, fig. 1</bibRefCitation>
). Second and third segments of rostrum are almost equal in length; third segment narrowing apically. Fore wings elongate, surpassing abdominal apex, with narrow hypocostal plate. Forewing vein sequence: R 2, furcating very close to basal cell; M 3, first furcation in basal third of the wing, second furcation in apical third; CuΑ 1 (
<bibRefCitation box="[898,1268,2011,2036]" pageId="7" pageNumber="165" refId="ref6203" refString="Gnezdilov, V. M. &amp; Poggi, F. (2014) First record of Nearctic issid planthopper Thionia simplex (Hemiptera: Fulgoroidea: Issidae) from Europe. Zoosystematica Rossica, 23 (2), 238 - 241." type="journal article">Gnezdilov &amp; Poggi 2014, fig. 2</bibRefCitation>
). Clavus long, open—Pcu+Α1 runs into apex of clavus. Pcu fusing Α1 after middle of clavus (
<bibRefCitation box="[1053,1419,151,176]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" refId="ref6203" refString="Gnezdilov, V. M. &amp; Poggi, F. (2014) First record of Nearctic issid planthopper Thionia simplex (Hemiptera: Fulgoroidea: Issidae) from Europe. Zoosystematica Rossica, 23 (2), 238 - 241." type="journal article">Gnezdilov &amp; Poggi 2014, fig. 1</bibRefCitation>
). Hind wings 3-lobed, with deep cubital cleft and without coupling lobe on its anterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[1212,1295,190,215]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–11" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1322,1345]" captionTargetBox="[533,1060,201,1303]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[525,1074,195,1311]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 9–11. Thioniina, hind wing. 9—Cheiloceps musca Uhler; 10—Cheiloceps argo (Fennah); 11—Aplos simplex (Germar). Abbreviations: rl—remigial lobe; rvl—remigio-vannal lobe; al—anal lobe." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1290890/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Hind wing vein sequence: R 2 r-m 1 M 1 m-cua 1 CuΑ 2 cua-cup 1 CuP 1 cup-pcu 1 Pcu 3 pcu-a1 1 Α1 2 Α2 2. Hind tibia with 2 lateral spines in its apical half. First metatarsomere with a whole row of spines arranged in arc. Dorso-lateral phallobase lobes fused dorsally, poorly sclerotized apically. Each dorso-lateral phallobase lobe with a large hookshaped apical process (
<bibRefCitation box="[408,676,337,362]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" refId="ref5415" refString="Doering, K. C. (1938) A contribution to the taxonomy of the subfamily Issinae in America north of Mexico (Fulgoridae, Homoptera). Part 2. The University of Kansas Science Bulletin, 25 (20), 447 - 575." type="journal article">Doering 1938, Pl. 55: 2</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="166" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,578]" box="[199,1179,373,398]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,373,398]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">Etymology.</emphasis>
Generic name derived from Greek “Απλός” (simple). Masculine in gender.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,578]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,359,409,434]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">Composition.</emphasis>
Αpparently 
<taxonomicName authority="(Say, 1830)" authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1830" baseAuthorityName="Say" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[498,808,409,434]" class="Insecta" family="Issidae" genus="Thionia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bullata">
<emphasis box="[498,671,409,434]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">Thionia bullata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation box="[687,799,410,434]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" refId="ref6575" refString="Say, T. (1830) Descriptions of new North American hemipterous insects, belonging to the first family of the section Homoptera of Latreille. Journal of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 6, 235 - 244." type="journal article">Say, 1830</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(originally 
<taxonomicName authority="Say, 1830" authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1830" box="[940,1205,409,434]" class="Insecta" family="Flatidae" genus="Flata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bullata">
<emphasis box="[940,1087,409,434]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">Flata bullata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[1094,1205,410,434]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" refId="ref6575" refString="Say, T. (1830) Descriptions of new North American hemipterous insects, belonging to the first family of the section Homoptera of Latreille. Journal of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 6, 235 - 244." type="journal article">Say, 1830</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) also belongs to this genus according to the structure of phallobase bearing hook-shaped apical process, however, this species differs from the type species by furcating subapically ventral aedeagal hooks (
<bibRefCitation box="[987,1283,481,506]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" refId="ref5415" refString="Doering, K. C. (1938) A contribution to the taxonomy of the subfamily Issinae in America north of Mexico (Fulgoridae, Homoptera). Part 2. The University of Kansas Science Bulletin, 25 (20), 447 - 575." type="journal article">Doering 1938, Pl. 55: 10</bibRefCitation>
) and distinct sublateral carinae of metope (
<bibRefCitation box="[481,695,517,542]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" refId="ref5213" refString="Bartlett, C. R., O'Brien, L. B. &amp; Wilson, S. W. (2014) A review of the planthoppers (Hemiptera: Fulgoroidea) of the United States. Memoires of the American Entomological Society, 50, 1 - 187." type="journal article">
Bartlett 
<emphasis box="[573,622,517,542]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 86D). The correct taxonomic position of this species needs to be confirmed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
